	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64398464"><p><span class="substr"> </span> <em>That's a DMCA nightmare.</em> </p><p>Actually the DMCA has <a href="https://ilt.eff.org/Copyright__Digital_Millennium_Copyright_Act.html#Functions_Covered_Under_DMCA_Safe_Harbors" title="eff.org">safe harbor available for system caches</a> [eff.org] - 17 USC 512(b).</p><p>A distributed cache  can be within the safe harbor.</p><p> <a href="https://research.ceb.com/secondary-sources/area/intellectual-property/15ilpx0000/eb11.73" title="ceb.com">Google ought to know about that one</a> [ceb.com] </p><blockquote><div><p>17 USC 512(b)(1). See Parker v Google (ED Pa 2006) 422 F Supp 2d 492, 497, aff'd (3d Cir 2007) 242 Fed Appx 833, cert denied (2008) 552 US 1156 (defendant, Google, entitled to safe harbor for automatic caching of web pages for indexing purposes);</p><p>Field v Google, Inc. (D Nev 2006) 412 F Supp 2d 1106 ("cached" links to plain</p></div></blockquote></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64398464">

